#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:5
msgid "NumPy 1.19.0 Release Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:6
msgid ""
"This NumPy release is marked by the removal of much technical debt: support "
"for Python 2 has been removed, many deprecations have been expired, and "
"documentation has been improved. The polishing of the random module "
"continues apace with bug fixes and better usability from Cython."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:11
msgid ""
"The Python versions supported for this release are 3.6-3.8. Downstream "
"developers should use Cython >= 0.29.16 for Python 3.8 support and OpenBLAS "
">= 3.7 to avoid problems on the Skylake architecture."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:17
msgid "Highlights"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:19
msgid ""
"Code compatibility with Python versions < 3.6 (including Python 2) was "
"dropped from both the python and C code. The shims in ``numpy.compat`` will "
"remain to support third-party packages, but they may be deprecated in a "
"future release. Note that 1.19.x will *not* compile with earlier versions of "
"Python due to the use of f-strings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:25
msgid "(`gh-15233 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15233>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:29
msgid "Expired deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:32
msgid ""
"``numpy.insert`` and ``numpy.delete`` can no longer be passed an axis on 0d "
"arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:33
msgid ""
"This concludes a deprecation from 1.9, where when an ``axis`` argument was "
"passed to a call to ``~numpy.insert`` and ``~numpy.delete`` on a 0d array, "
"the ``axis`` and ``obj`` argument and indices would be completely ignored. "
"In these cases, ``insert(arr, \"nonsense\", 42, axis=0)`` would actually "
"overwrite the entire array, while ``delete(arr, \"nonsense\", axis=0)`` "
"would be ``arr.copy()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:39
msgid "Now passing ``axis`` on a 0d array raises ``~numpy.AxisError``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:41
msgid "(`gh-15802 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15802>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:44
msgid "``numpy.delete`` no longer ignores out-of-bounds indices"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:45
msgid ""
"This concludes deprecations from 1.8 and 1.9, where ``np.delete`` would "
"ignore both negative and out-of-bounds items in a sequence of indices. This "
"was at odds with its behavior when passed a single index."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:49
msgid ""
"Now out-of-bounds items throw ``IndexError``, and negative items index from "
"the end."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:52
msgid "(`gh-15804 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15804>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:55
msgid ""
"``numpy.insert`` and ``numpy.delete`` no longer accept non-integral indices"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:56
msgid ""
"This concludes a deprecation from 1.9, where sequences of non-integers "
"indices were allowed and cast to integers. Now passing sequences of non-"
"integral indices raises ``IndexError``, just like it does when passing a "
"single non-integral scalar."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:61
msgid "(`gh-15805 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15805>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:64
msgid "``numpy.delete`` no longer casts boolean indices to integers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:65
msgid ""
"This concludes a deprecation from 1.8, where ``np.delete`` would cast "
"boolean arrays and scalars passed as an index argument into integer indices. "
"The behavior now is to treat boolean arrays as a mask, and to raise an error "
"on boolean scalars."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:70
msgid "(`gh-15815 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15815>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:74
msgid "Compatibility notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:77
msgid "Changed random variate stream from ``numpy.random.Generator.dirichlet``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:78
msgid ""
"A bug in the generation of random variates for the Dirichlet distribution "
"with small 'alpha' values was fixed by using a different algorithm when "
"``max(alpha) < 0.1``.  Because of the change, the stream of variates "
"generated by ``dirichlet`` in this case will be different from previous "
"releases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:84
msgid "(`gh-14924 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/14924>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:87
msgid "Scalar promotion in ``PyArray_ConvertToCommonType``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:88
msgid ""
"The promotion of mixed scalars and arrays in ``PyArray_ConvertToCommonType`` "
"has been changed to adhere to those used by ``np.result_type``. This means "
"that input such as ``(1000, np.array([1], dtype=np.uint8)))`` will now "
"return ``uint16`` dtypes. In most cases the behaviour is unchanged. Note "
"that the use of this C-API function is generally discouraged. This also "
"fixes ``np.choose`` to behave the same way as the rest of NumPy in this "
"respect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:96
msgid "(`gh-14933 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/14933>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:99
msgid "Fasttake and fastputmask slots are deprecated and NULL'ed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:100
msgid ""
"The fasttake and fastputmask slots are now never used and must always be set "
"to NULL. This will result in no change in behaviour. However, if a user "
"dtype should set one of these a DeprecationWarning will be given."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:105
msgid "(`gh-14942 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/14942>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:108
msgid "``np.ediff1d`` casting behaviour with ``to_end`` and ``to_begin``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:109
msgid ""
"``np.ediff1d`` now uses the ``\"same_kind\"`` casting rule for its "
"additional ``to_end`` and ``to_begin`` arguments. This ensures type safety "
"except when the input array has a smaller integer type than ``to_begin`` or "
"``to_end``. In rare cases, the behaviour will be more strict than it was "
"previously in 1.16 and 1.17. This is necessary to solve issues with floating "
"point NaN."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:117
msgid "(`gh-14981 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/14981>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:120
msgid "Converting of empty array-like objects to NumPy arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:121
msgid ""
"Objects with ``len(obj) == 0`` which implement an \"array-like\" interface, "
"meaning an object implementing ``obj.__array__()``, ``obj."
"__array_interface__``, ``obj.__array_struct__``, or the python buffer "
"interface and which are also sequences (i.e. Pandas objects) will now always "
"retain there shape correctly when converted to an array. If such an object "
"has a shape of ``(0, 1)`` previously, it could be converted into an array of "
"shape ``(0,)`` (losing all dimensions after the first 0)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:130
msgid "(`gh-14995 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/14995>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:133
msgid "Removed ``multiarray.int_asbuffer``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:134
msgid ""
"As part of the continued removal of Python 2 compatibility, ``multiarray."
"int_asbuffer`` was removed. On Python 3, it threw a ``NotImplementedError`` "
"and was unused internally. It is expected that there are no downstream use "
"cases for this method with Python 3."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:139
msgid "(`gh-15229 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15229>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:142
msgid "``numpy.distutils.compat`` has been removed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:143
msgid ""
"This module contained only the function ``get_exception()``, which was used "
"as::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:145
msgid ""
"try:\n"
"    ...\n"
"except Exception:\n"
"    e = get_exception()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:150
msgid ""
"Its purpose was to handle the change in syntax introduced in Python 2.6, "
"from ``except Exception, e:`` to ``except Exception as e:``, meaning it was "
"only necessary for codebases supporting Python 2.5 and older."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:154
msgid "(`gh-15255 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15255>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:157
msgid "``issubdtype`` no longer interprets ``float`` as ``np.floating``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:158
msgid ""
"``numpy.issubdtype`` had a FutureWarning since NumPy 1.14 which has expired "
"now. This means that certain input where the second argument was neither a "
"datatype nor a NumPy scalar type (such as a string or a python type like "
"``int`` or ``float``) will now be consistent with passing in ``np."
"dtype(arg2).type``. This makes the result consistent with expectations and "
"leads to a false result in some cases which previously returned true."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:166
msgid "(`gh-15773 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15773>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:169
msgid "Change output of ``round`` on scalars to be consistent with Python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:171
msgid ""
"Output of the ``__round__`` dunder method and consequently the Python built-"
"in ``round`` has been changed to be a Python ``int`` to be consistent with "
"calling it on Python ``float`` objects when called with no arguments. "
"Previously, it would return a scalar of the ``np.dtype`` that was passed in."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:176 ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:276
msgid "(`gh-15840 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15840>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:179
msgid ""
"The ``numpy.ndarray`` constructor no longer interprets ``strides=()`` as "
"``strides=None``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:180
msgid ""
"The former has changed to have the expected meaning of setting ``numpy."
"ndarray.strides`` to ``()``, while the latter continues to result in strides "
"being chosen automatically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:184
msgid "(`gh-15882 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15882>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:187
msgid "C-Level string to datetime casts changed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:188
msgid ""
"The C-level casts from strings were simplified. This changed also fixes "
"string to datetime and timedelta casts to behave correctly (i.e. like Python "
"casts using ``string_arr.astype(\"M8\")`` while previously the cast would "
"behave like ``string_arr.astype(np.int_).astype(\"M8\")``. This only affects "
"code using low-level C-API to do manual casts (not full array casts) of "
"single scalar values or using e.g. ``PyArray_GetCastFunc``, and should thus "
"not affect the vast majority of users."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:198
msgid "(`gh-16068 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16068>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:201
msgid "``SeedSequence`` with small seeds no longer conflicts with spawning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:202
msgid ""
"Small seeds (less than ``2**96``) were previously implicitly 0-padded out to "
"128 bits, the size of the internal entropy pool. When spawned, the spawn key "
"was concatenated before the 0-padding. Since the first spawn key is "
"``(0,)``, small seeds before the spawn created the same states as the first "
"spawned ``SeedSequence``.  Now, the seed is explicitly 0-padded out to the "
"internal pool size before concatenating the spawn key. Spawned "
"``SeedSequences`` will produce different results than in the previous "
"release. Unspawned ``SeedSequences`` will still produce the same results."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:211
msgid "(`gh-16551 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16551>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:215
msgid "Deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:218
msgid "Deprecate automatic ``dtype=object`` for ragged input"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:219
msgid ""
"Calling ``np.array([[1, [1, 2, 3]])`` will issue a ``DeprecationWarning`` as "
"per `NEP 34`_. Users should explicitly use ``dtype=object`` to avoid the "
"warning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:225
msgid "(`gh-15119 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15119>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:228
msgid "Passing ``shape=0`` to factory functions in ``numpy.rec`` is deprecated"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:229
msgid ""
"``0`` is treated as a special case and is aliased to ``None`` in the "
"functions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:231
msgid "``numpy.core.records.fromarrays``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:232
msgid "``numpy.core.records.fromrecords``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:233
msgid "``numpy.core.records.fromstring``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:234
msgid "``numpy.core.records.fromfile``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:236
msgid ""
"In future, ``0`` will not be special cased, and will be treated as an array "
"length like any other integer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:239
msgid "(`gh-15217 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15217>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:242
msgid "Deprecation of probably unused C-API functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:243
msgid ""
"The following C-API functions are probably unused and have been deprecated:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:246
msgid "``PyArray_GetArrayParamsFromObject``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:247
msgid "``PyUFunc_GenericFunction``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:248
msgid "``PyUFunc_SetUsesArraysAsData``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:250
msgid ""
"In most cases ``PyArray_GetArrayParamsFromObject`` should be replaced by "
"converting to an array, while ``PyUFunc_GenericFunction`` can be replaced "
"with ``PyObject_Call`` (see documentation for details)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:254
msgid "(`gh-15427 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15427>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:257
msgid "Converting certain types to dtypes is Deprecated"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:258
msgid ""
"The super classes of scalar types, such as ``np.integer``, ``np.generic``, "
"or ``np.inexact`` will now give a deprecation warning when converted to a "
"dtype (or used in a dtype keyword argument). The reason for this is that "
"``np.integer`` is converted to ``np.int_``, while it would be expected to "
"represent *any* integer (e.g. also ``int8``, ``int16``, etc. For example, "
"``dtype=np.floating`` is currently identical to ``dtype=np.float64``, even "
"though also ``np.float32`` is a subclass of ``np.floating``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:268
msgid "(`gh-15534 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15534>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:271
msgid "Deprecation of ``round`` for ``np.complexfloating`` scalars"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:272
msgid ""
"Output of the ``__round__`` dunder method and consequently the Python built-"
"in ``round`` has been deprecated on complex scalars. This does not affect "
"``np.round``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:279
msgid "``numpy.ndarray.tostring()`` is deprecated in favor of ``tobytes()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:280
msgid ""
"``~numpy.ndarray.tobytes`` has existed since the 1.9 release, but until this "
"release ``~numpy.ndarray.tostring`` emitted no warning. The change to emit a "
"warning brings NumPy in line with the builtin ``array.array`` methods of the "
"same name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:285
msgid "(`gh-15867 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15867>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:289
msgid "C API changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:292
msgid "Better support for ``const`` dimensions in API functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:293
msgid "The following functions now accept a constant array of ``npy_intp``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:295
msgid "``PyArray_BroadcastToShape``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:296
msgid "``PyArray_IntTupleFromIntp``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:297
msgid "``PyArray_OverflowMultiplyList``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:299
msgid ""
"Previously the caller would have to cast away the const-ness to call these "
"functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:302
msgid "(`gh-15251 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15251>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:305
msgid "Const qualify UFunc inner loops"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:306
msgid ""
"``UFuncGenericFunction`` now expects pointers to const ``dimension`` and "
"``strides`` as arguments. This means inner loops may no longer modify either "
"``dimension`` or ``strides``. This change leads to an ``incompatible-pointer-"
"types`` warning forcing users to either ignore the compiler warnings or to "
"const qualify their own loop signatures."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:312
msgid "(`gh-15355 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15355>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:316
msgid "New Features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:319
msgid "``numpy.frompyfunc`` now accepts an identity argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:320
msgid ""
"This allows the :attr:`numpy.ufunc.identity` attribute to be set on the "
"resulting ufunc, meaning it can be used for empty and multi-dimensional "
"calls to :meth:`numpy.ufunc.reduce`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:324
msgid "(`gh-8255 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/8255>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:327
msgid "``np.str_`` scalars now support the buffer protocol"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:328
msgid ""
"``np.str_`` arrays are always stored as UCS4, so the corresponding scalars "
"now expose this through the buffer interface, meaning ``memoryview(np."
"str_('test'))`` now works."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:332
msgid "(`gh-15385 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15385>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:335
msgid "``subok`` option for ``numpy.copy``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:336
msgid ""
"A new kwarg, ``subok``, was added to ``numpy.copy`` to allow users to toggle "
"the behavior of ``numpy.copy`` with respect to array subclasses. The default "
"value is ``False`` which is consistent with the behavior of ``numpy.copy`` "
"for previous numpy versions. To create a copy that preserves an array "
"subclass with ``numpy.copy``, call ``np.copy(arr, subok=True)``. This "
"addition better documents that the default behavior of ``numpy.copy`` "
"differs from the ``numpy.ndarray.copy`` method which respects array "
"subclasses by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:344
msgid "(`gh-15685 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15685>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:347
msgid "``numpy.linalg.multi_dot`` now accepts an ``out`` argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:349
msgid ""
"``out`` can be used to avoid creating unnecessary copies of the final "
"product computed by ``numpy.linalg.multidot``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:352
msgid "(`gh-15715 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15715>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:355
msgid "``keepdims`` parameter for ``numpy.count_nonzero``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:356
msgid ""
"The parameter ``keepdims`` was added to ``numpy.count_nonzero``. The "
"parameter has the same meaning as it does in reduction functions such as "
"``numpy.sum`` or ``numpy.mean``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:360
msgid "(`gh-15870 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15870>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:363
msgid "``equal_nan`` parameter for ``numpy.array_equal``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:364
msgid ""
"The keyword argument ``equal_nan`` was added to ``numpy.array_equal``. "
"``equal_nan`` is a boolean value that toggles whether or not ``nan`` values "
"are considered equal in comparison (default is ``False``). This matches API "
"used in related functions such as ``numpy.isclose`` and ``numpy.allclose``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:369
msgid "(`gh-16128 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16128>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:373
msgid "Improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:376
msgid "Improve detection of CPU features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:377
msgid ""
"Replace ``npy_cpu_supports`` which was a gcc specific mechanism to test "
"support of AVX with more general functions ``npy_cpu_init`` and "
"``npy_cpu_have``, and expose the results via a ``NPY_CPU_HAVE`` c-macro as "
"well as a python-level ``__cpu_features__`` dictionary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:382
msgid "(`gh-13421 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/13421>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:385
msgid "Use 64-bit integer size on 64-bit platforms in fallback lapack_lite"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:386
msgid ""
"Use 64-bit integer size on 64-bit platforms in the fallback LAPACK library, "
"which is used when the system has no LAPACK installed, allowing it to deal "
"with linear algebra for large arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:390
msgid "(`gh-15218 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15218>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:393
msgid ""
"Use AVX512 intrinsic to implement ``np.exp`` when input is ``np.float64``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:394
msgid ""
"Use AVX512 intrinsic to implement ``np.exp`` when input is ``np.float64``, "
"which can improve the performance of ``np.exp`` with ``np.float64`` input "
"5-7x faster than before. The ``_multiarray_umath.so`` module has grown about "
"63 KB on linux64."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:399
msgid "(`gh-15648 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15648>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:402
msgid "Ability to disable madvise hugepages"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:403
msgid ""
"On Linux NumPy has previously added support for madavise hugepages which can "
"improve performance for very large arrays.  Unfortunately, on older Kernel "
"versions this led to performance regressions, thus by default the support "
"has been disabled on kernels before version 4.6. To override the default, "
"you can use the environment variable::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:409
msgid "NUMPY_MADVISE_HUGEPAGE=0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:411
msgid ""
"or set it to 1 to force enabling support. Note that this only makes a "
"difference if the operating system is set up to use madvise transparent "
"hugepage."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:415
msgid "(`gh-15769 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15769>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:418
msgid "``numpy.einsum`` accepts NumPy ``int64`` type in subscript list"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:419
msgid ""
"There is no longer a type error thrown when ``numpy.einsum`` is passed a "
"NumPy ``int64`` array as its subscript list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:422
msgid "(`gh-16080 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16080>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:425
msgid "``np.logaddexp2.identity`` changed to ``-inf``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:426
msgid ""
"The ufunc ``~numpy.logaddexp2`` now has an identity of ``-inf``, allowing it "
"to be called on empty sequences.  This matches the identity of ``~numpy."
"logaddexp``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:429
msgid "(`gh-16102 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16102>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:433
msgid "Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:436
msgid "Remove handling of extra argument to ``__array__``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:437
msgid ""
"A code path and test have been in the code since NumPy 0.4 for a two-"
"argument variant of ``__array__(dtype=None, context=None)``. It was "
"activated when calling ``ufunc(op)`` or ``ufunc.reduce(op)`` if ``op."
"__array__`` existed. However that variant is not documented, and it is not "
"clear what the intention was for its use. It has been removed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:443
msgid "(`gh-15118 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15118>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:446
msgid "``numpy.random._bit_generator`` moved to ``numpy.random.bit_generator``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:447
msgid ""
"In order to expose ``numpy.random.BitGenerator`` and ``numpy.random."
"SeedSequence`` to Cython, the ``_bitgenerator`` module is now public as "
"``numpy.random.bit_generator``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:452
msgid ""
"Cython access to the random distributions is provided via a ``pxd`` file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:453
msgid ""
"``c_distributions.pxd`` provides access to the c functions behind many of "
"the random distributions from Cython, making it convenient to use and extend "
"them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:456
msgid "(`gh-15463 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15463>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:459
msgid ""
"Fixed ``eigh`` and ``cholesky`` methods in ``numpy.random."
"multivariate_normal``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:460
msgid ""
"Previously, when passing ``method='eigh'`` or ``method='cholesky'``, ``numpy."
"random.multivariate_normal`` produced samples from the wrong distribution. "
"This is now fixed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:464
msgid "(`gh-15872 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15872>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:467
msgid "Fixed the jumping implementation in ``MT19937.jumped``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:468
msgid ""
"This fix changes the stream produced from jumped MT19937 generators. It does "
"not affect the stream produced using ``RandomState`` or ``MT19937`` that are "
"directly seeded."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.19.0-notes.rst:472
msgid ""
"The translation of the jumping code for the MT19937 contained a reversed "
"loop ordering. ``MT19937.jumped`` matches the Makoto Matsumoto's original "
"implementation of the Horner and Sliding Window jump methods."
msgstr ""

